-- Japan, India, Malaysia, South Korea, Taiwan: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-07-07T21:55:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-07/japan-india-malaysia-south-korea-taiwan-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 Bank of Japan Governor  Masaaki Shirakawa  will make the
opening speech at the central bank’s meeting of branch managers
that starts at 9 a.m.  
 The Cabinet Office will release at 8:50 a.m. its report on
machinery orders for May. Orders, an indicator of business
investment in three to six months, fell 3 percent from April,
when they rose 4 percent, according to a Bloomberg News survey
of economists.  
 The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. its
report on Japan’s current-account balance. The surplus will
widen to 1.3 trillion yen ($14.9 billion) in May from 1.2
trillion yen in April, a separate Bloomberg survey showed.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.125 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 87.78 per dollar at 6:47 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The finance ministry plans to sell 20 billion yuan
($3 billion) of 182-day bills tomorrow. The People’s Bank of
China plans to sell 10 billion yuan of three-month bills today.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.59 percent. The yuan was at 6.7772 per dollar.  
 India: The government will report primary articles
inflation, which includes changes in food prices, for the week
ended June 26. An index measuring wholesale costs of farm
products including lentils, rice and vegetables, a component of
the primary articles gauge, rose 12.9 percent in the previous
week from a year earlier.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.57
percent. The rupee was at 47.03.  
 Malaysia: The central bank will review benchmark interest
rates at a policy meeting today. Half of the 20 economists in a
Bloomberg News survey predicted Bank Negara Malaysia will
increase its benchmark overnight policy rate to 2.75 percent
from 2.5 percent. The other half expect no change. The central
bank raised borrowing costs by a combined half a percentage
point in March and May.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.48 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.22.  
 South Korea: The central bank will hold its benchmark rate
at a record low of 2 percent at a meeting tomorrow, according to
the median estimate of 14 economists surveyed by Bloomberg.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.44 percent. The won was at 1,216.50.  
 Taiwan: A government report may show that the nation’s
exports grew 45.8 percent in June from a year earlier, after
rising 57.9 percent the previous month, according to the median
estimate of 12 economists surveyed by Bloomberg. The report may
also show Taiwan’s trade surplus narrowed to $2.6 billion last
month from $3.25 billion in May, according to the survey.  
 The yield on the 1.375 percent bond maturing March 2020 was
1.40 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar traded at NT$32.22.  
